The Ministry of Health on Saturday announced
that Kenya had recorded 15 new COVID-19 cases from a sample size of 4,549
tested in the last 24 hours, marking a positivity rate of 0.3%. From
the cases, 9 are Kenyans while 6 are foreigners; 10 are males and 5 are
females. The youngest is 22 years old while the oldest is 82 years. Total
confirmed positive cases are now 323,365 while cumulative tests so far
conducted are at 3,495,960. The
cases were distributed across seven counties; Nairobi led with 8, followed by
Siaya with 2. Homa Bay, Kisumu, Nyamira, Uasin Gishu and Kirinyaga each had one
case. The
ministry also said 11 patients are admitted in various health facilities
countrywide, while 135 are under the Home-Based Isolation and Care program and
one patient is on ventilatory support at the Intensive Care Unit (ICU). "Another
3 patients are on supplemental oxygen and all of them are in the general wards.
No patient is in the High Dependency Unit (HDU)," Health Cabinet Secretary
Mutahi Kagwe said in a statement. Meanwhile,
15 patients have recovered from the disease, all of them from Home-Based and
Isolation Care. This pushes the total recoveries to 317,572. CS
Kagwe further noted that no deaths were reported, therefore cumulative
fatalities still stand at 5,647. On
the vaccination exercise, CS Kagwe announced that 17,504,467 vaccines had been
administered across the country as of March 25, 2022. Of
these, he said, 16,024,290 are doses administered to the adult population (18
years and above). Another
1,204,481 are doses administered to those between 15 to 17 years while 275,525
are booster doses. “The
total number of vaccines administered in the last 24 hours is 27,561,” stated
the CS.  “Proportion
of adults fully vaccinated was 29.5%. The government is working towards
vaccinating a targeted population of 27,246,033.”